rComments: One of the standout professors in all of U of T. Extremely approachable and helpful, tries her best to make sure all of her students succeed. The material can be tough and requires heavy analysis and lots of asking questions, she normally teaches graduate classes so I think she may expect more out of the average student.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Gives good feedback', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: This was a theory class and focused on typical philosophers.  Concepts focused on the "state" and power rather than actual crime or law. You had to attend lectures to get notes- no powerpoints or slides posted. You also had to handwrite, no computers allowed. Valverde made the best out of a really boring subject. Tests were creative but difficult

World class prof. highly intelligent, open minded, and helpful.  Takes the time with students who want to invest it. A happy anomaly in a post-secondary education system that is rapidly becoming commoditized and trivial.  Highly influential on my career path, one of the finest thinkers Iâ€™ve ever encountered and a great all round person.

She has good lecture notes, however she isn't much help outside of lecture material, she will refer you to the TA's, which for this class were even more useless. A pylon could have done a better job at being TA. However, she does answer questions relatively well.

WDW387: Legal Regulation -I found her to be completely approachable, helpful, open minded, articulate, extremely  knowledgeable, & a memorable lecturer. Ask good questions in class, bring knowledge of intersectionalities for a different perspective & you will do well w/ her. She expects a lot. I didn't get an A but I loved the class & learned a lot

Really nice and very helpful. Has a very positive attitude and won't make you feel stupid for asking questions no matter how obvious the answer.
